07050nam a22008415i 9780674270534DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20211996mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742705347 a10.4159/97806742705342doi  a(DE-B1597)589751  a(OCoLC)1262307189  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPSY0260002bisacsh04a616.85/2100aTrauma and Dreams /ced. by Deirdre. Barrett. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (282 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One Dreams after Childhood Trauma -- t1 Children’s Traumatic Dreams -- t2 Dreams and Nightmares of Burned Children -- t3 Identifying Sexual Trauma Histories from Patterns of Sleep and Dream -- t4 The Use of Dreams with Incest Survivors -- t5 Dreams in Multiple Personality Disorder -- tPart Two Adult Trauma in Wars and Natural Disaster -- t6 The Healing Nightmare: War Dreams of Vietnam V -- t7 Who Develops PTSD Nightmares and Who Doesn’t -- t8 Sleep, Dreaming, and Coping Style in Holocaust Survivors -- t9 Dreaming Well: On Death and History -- t10 The Collective Nightmare of Central American Refugees -- t11 Jasmine: Dreams in the Psychotherapy of a Rape Survivor -- t12 Dreams of Firestorm Survivors -- tPart Three Traumas of Normal Living -- t13 Dreams and Adaptation to Divorce -- t14 Dreams in Bereavement -- t15 Neurological Dreams -- t16 Integration and Ambivalence in Transplants -- t17 Recurrent Dreams: Their Relation to Life Eve -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAccording to the poet Elias Canetti, "All the things one has forgotten / scream for help in dreams." To the ancient Egyptians they were prophecies, and in world folklore they have often marked visitations from the dead. For Freud they were expressions of "wish fulfillment," and for Jung, symbolic representations of mythical archetypes. Although there is still much disagreement about the significance and function of dreams, they seem to serve as a barometer of current mind and body states. In this volume, Deirdre Barrett brings together the study of dreams and the psychology of trauma. She has called on a distinguished group of psychiatrists, psychologists, and social workers--among them Rosalind Cartwright, Robert J. Lifton, and Oliver Sacks--to consider how trauma shapes dreaming and what the dreaming mind might reveal about trauma. The book focuses on catastrophic events, such as combat, political torture, natural disasters, and rape. The lasting effects of childhood trauma, such as sexual abuse or severe burns, on personality formation, the nature of memories of early trauma, and the development of defenses related to amnesia and dissociation are all considered. The book also takes up trauma and adult dreams, including Vietnam veterans and Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder, Holocaust survivors and perpetrators, rape victims, and firestorm survivors. Finally, this volume concludes with a look at the potential "traumas of normal life," such as divorce, bereavement, and life-threatening illness, and the role of dreams in working through normal grief and loss. Taken together, these diverse perspectives illuminate the universal and the particular effects of traumatic experience. For physicians and clinicians, determining the etiology of nightmares offers valuable diagnostic and therapeutic insights for individual treatment. This book provides a way of juxtaposing the research in the separate fields of trauma and dreams, and learning from their discoveries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh1 aAron, Adrianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Deirdre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Deirdre., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBelicki, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosnak, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartwright, Rosalind D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChedekel, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuddy, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarfield, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartmann, Ernest, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaminer, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavie, Peretz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLifton, Robert Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuller, Karen Hagerman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNader, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSacks, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheehan, Jacqueline R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegel, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoddard, Frederick J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilmer, Harry A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZadra, Antonio L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674270534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97806742705